   "source": [
    "## Key Findings \n",
    "\n",
    "### Research Q4 (Song Length Sweet Spot)\n",
    "- The relationship between song length and popularity is **non-linear**: the middle quantiles perform best, while both extremes are lower.\n",
    "- Mean popularity by duration bucket was:\n",
    "  - **Q1 shortest:** 31.14\n",
    "  - **Q2:** 32.50\n",
    "  - **Q3:** 35.20 *(highest)*\n",
    "  - **Q4:** 35.02\n",
    "  - **Q5 longest:** 32.42\n",
    "- This suggests a practical “sweet spot” around **mid-length tracks** (Q3–Q4), which outperform both very short and very long songs by about **3 to 4 popularity points**.\n",
    "- Interpretation: duration appears to matter, but mostly as a balancing factor, tracks that are not too short or too long tend to perform better on average.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Research Q5 (Collaboration Effect)\n",
